<title>SWEDEN: P&amp;U SUES NYCOMED OVER PATENT - REPORT.</title>
<headline>P&amp;U SUES NYCOMED OVER PATENT - REPORT.</headline>
<dateline>STOCKHOLM 1997-08-10</dateline>
<text>
<p>Swedish-U.S. drug company Pharmacia &amp; Upjohn (P&amp;U) is suing the Swedish unit of rival Nycomed ASA for 31.5 million crowns over patent infringement, Swedish daily Svenska Dagbladet said on Sunday.</p>
<p>P&amp;U says sales of its breast cancer drug Adriamycin fell 40 percent when Nycomed AB in Sweden launched a lower-priced comparable treatment, which P&amp;U says it has the patent for, the newspaper said.</p>
<p>&quot;...P&amp;U is demanding that Nycomed immediately discontinue selling the drug, which is sold in Sweden under the brand name Doxorubicin Nycomed,&quot; Svenska Dagbladet said.</p>
<p>P&amp;U says it was forced to cut prices by 20 percent to compete with the Nycomed treatment, Svenska Dagbladet said.</p>
<p>P&amp;U also had to reduce the price on Farmorubicin, another cancer drug, the newspaper said.</p>
<p>Norwegian drugs company Nycomed ASA plans to merge with Britain's Amersham Internationl Plc.</p>
<p>-- Abigail Schmelz, Stockholm newsroom +46-8-700-1003</p>
